Further differences between both species are the lower number of spines on the lateral portion of the uropodal diaeresis (one in 

E. puteola

vs. 
2–3 in

E. edingtonae

); the lateral tooth of the scaphocerite falling short of the distal margin of the lamella (vs. far over reaching in 

E. edingtonae

); the absence of a spine on the merus of the ambulatory pereiopods (present in 

E. edingtonae

); the absence of a podobranch on the second maxilliped (present, albeit reduced in 

E. edingtonae

) and the absence of appendices internae on the male pleopods 2-5 (present in 

E. edingtonae

).
